---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SectionHead from '../../components/SectionHead.astro';
import ArrowLink from '../../components/ArrowLink.astro';
import GovernanceHierarchy from '../../components/diagrams/GovernanceHierarchy.astro';
import { externalLinks } from '../../config';
import { getCollection } from 'astro:content';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/TableOfContents.astro';

const authorities = (await getCollection('authority'))
  .map((c) => ({
    id: c.id,
    identifier: String((c.data as Record<string, unknown>).authorityIdentifier ?? c.id),
    name: String((c.data as Record<string, unknown>).name ?? c.id),
  }))
  .sort((a, b) => a.identifier.localeCompare(b.identifier));

const variaAuthority = authorities.find((a) => a.identifier === 'Var') ?? null;
const selfManagedAuthorities = authorities.filter((a) => a.identifier !== 'Var');
const tocItems = [{ "id": "purpose",
  "label": "Purpose" },
  { "id": "scope",
  "label": "Scope" },
  { "id": "governance",
  "label": "Governance" },
  { "id": "authorities",
  "label": "Authorities in the register" },
  { "id": "uris",
  "label": "URIs" },
  { "id": "reference-standards",
  "label": "Reference standards" },
  { "id": "logomark",
  "label": "The logomark" },
  { "id": "colours",
  "label": "The colours" }];
---

<Layout title="About">
  {/* ── Hero ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="mb-16">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-4">About</p>
    <h1 class="max-w-4xl mb-6">The international standard for writing system conversion systems.</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-ink-muted max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
      ISO 24229 gives every system that converts text from one script or spelling to another — transliteration, transcription, romanisation, and orthographic reform alike — a single, unambiguous identifier. This website is the official register, operated by CalConnect as Registration Authority, designated by ISO.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="lg:grid lg:grid-cols-[180px_1fr] lg:gap-12">
    <TableOfContents items={tocItems} />
    <div>

  {/* ── Purpose ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section id="purpose" class="rule-section">
    <SectionHead eyebrow="Purpose" title="Why this standard exists." />
    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        A number of international applications require the identification of writing system conversion systems — terminology, lexicography, bibliography, and linguistics, especially for reverse transliteration, computational linguistics, and machine pronunciation.
      </p>
      <p>
        The term <em>writing system conversion</em> is intended to refer to all types of transformations of written texts from one spelling system to another. It includes both script conversion (change of script: transliteration, transcription) and conversion of texts without changing the script (e.g. transcription of foreign names or words using the alphabet of a target language, change of the orthography in a language).
      </p>
      <p>
        ISO 24229 is one of three important ISO standards for internationalisation, alongside the <a href={externalLinks.iso639Standard} class="underline">ISO 639</a> series (language codes) and <a href={externalLinks.iso15924Standard} class="underline">ISO 15924</a> (script codes). Together, they let any written form of any language be identified unambiguously.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Scope ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section id="scope" class="rule-section">
    <SectionHead eyebrow="Scope" title="What the standard defines." />
    <ul class="max-w-2xl space-y-3 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
      <li>Conversion system codes — structured identifiers for writing system conversion systems</li>
      <li>Spelling system codes — identifiers for the source and target forms being converted</li>
      <li>Conversion system authorities — identifiers for the bodies that manage conversion systems</li>
      <li>Requirements and processes for registering codes and authorities</li>
      <li>Data models for the codes and the metadata associated with them</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  {/* ── Governance ─────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section id="governance" class="rule-section">
    <SectionHead eyebrow="Governance" title="How the register is managed." />
    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed mb-8">
      <p>
        <a href={externalLinks.calconnect} class="underline">CalConnect</a> is the Registration Authority (ISO 24229/RA), designated by ISO. The register is operated by <a href={externalLinks.ribose} class="underline">Ribose</a>. An Advisory Group (ISO 24229/AG) of 4–12 experts — including a representative of ISO/TC 46 — reviews submissions at its bimonthly meeting. As a rule, decisions are made by consensus; if a vote is needed, a decision is approved when more than two-thirds of members vote for it.
      </p>
    </div>
    <GovernanceHierarchy />
    <p class="mt-6 text-sm">
      <ArrowLink href="/specs/governance" variant="muted">Full governance and lifecycle</ArrowLink>
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* ── Authorities directory ─────────────────────────────── */}
  <section id="authorities" class="rule-section">
    <SectionHead eyebrow="Authorities" title="Who manages each entry." />
    <p class="text-ink-muted max-w-2xl leading-relaxed mb-8">
      Most authorities maintain their own entries directly — they appoint two authorised persons (per Annex A.4) who can submit changes on the authority's behalf. The Varia authority (<span class="font-mono">Var</span>) is the exception: the Advisory Group itself manages it on behalf of the community, for systems that need representation but have no clear extant authority.
    </p>

    {variaAuthority && (
      <div class="mb-8 border-l-2 border-gold/60 dark:border-gold-bright/60 pl-5 py-2">
        <p class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink">Managed by the Advisory Group</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-1 mb-3">For systems without a clear extant authority — typically historic systems, or systems in active use across many libraries with no single owner.</p>
        <a href={`/register/authority/${variaAuthority.id}`} class="inline-flex items-baseline gap-3 group">
          <span class="font-mono text-sm text-blue dark:text-blue-bright group-hover:underline">{variaAuthority.identifier}</span>
          <span class="text-sm text-ink group-hover:text-gold-deep dark:group-hover:text-gold-bright transition-colors">{variaAuthority.name}</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    )}

    <div>
      <p class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink mb-3">Managed by the authority itself</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mb-4">Each authority designates two authorised persons who can submit changes. The current directory lists {selfManagedAuthorities.length} authorities.</p>
      <ul class="border-t border-rule">
        {selfManagedAuthorities.slice(0, 24).map((a) => (
          <li class="border-b border-rule">
            <a href={`/register/authority/${a.id}`} class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4 py-2.5 group">
              <span class="flex items-baseline gap-3 min-w-0">
                <span class="font-mono text-sm text-blue dark:text-blue-bright group-hover:underline shrink-0">{a.identifier}</span>
                <span class="text-sm text-ink group-hover:text-gold-deep dark:group-hover:text-gold-bright transition-colors truncate">{a.name}</span>
              </span>
              <span aria-hidden="true" class="text-ink-subtle text-xs shrink-0">→</span>
            </a>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
      {selfManagedAuthorities.length > 24 && (
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm">
          <a href="/register/authority" class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">Browse all {selfManagedAuthorities.length} authorities →</a>
        </p>
      )}
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── URIs ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section id="uris" class="rule-section">
    <SectionHead eyebrow="Identifiers" title="A URN for every entry." />
    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Every register entry has a canonical, location-independent identifier — a Uniform Resource Name issued under the <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5141" class="underline">RFC 5141</a> <span class="font-mono">urn:iso:</span> namespace. The URN is the machine-readable twin of the human-readable code; it is what citation systems, Linked Data consumers, and digital libraries should record.
      </p>
      <p>
        The pattern is <span class="font-mono">urn:iso:24229:&lt;itemClass&gt;:&lt;localId&gt;</span>:
      </p>
      <div class="border border-rule rounded bg-paper-raised p-5 font-mono text-sm space-y-2">
        <p><span class="text-gold-deep dark:text-gold-bright">urn:iso:24229:system</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">ahl:heb-Hebr:Latn:2011</span></p>
        <p><span class="text-gold-deep dark:text-gold-bright">urn:iso:24229:authority</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">ahl</span></p>
        <p><span class="text-gold-deep dark:text-gold-bright">urn:iso:24229:spelling</span><span class="text-ink-subtle">:</span><span class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright">heb-Hebr</span></p>
      </div>
      <p>
        Each system-code entry's URN embeds the four-segment colon-form code as its local identifier, so the URN and the code carry the same information in two forms. The code is what humans cite in prose; the URN is what machines record in metadata, RDF graphs, and catalogue records.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Reference standards ─────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section id="reference-standards" class="rule-section">
    <SectionHead eyebrow="Reference standards" title="ISO 24229 is one of three ISO standards that together identify any written form of any language. The other two have their own registration authorities." />
    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-6 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">

      <div class="border-l-2 border-blue/50 dark:border-blue-bright/50 pl-5">
        <p class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink mb-1">ISO 639 — language codes</p>
        <p class="text-sm mb-3">A family of standards covering four parts, each with its own maintenance agency (a "Language Coding Agency" or LCA). ISO 24229 references ISO 639 codes by their terminological form when one exists.</p>
        <ul class="text-sm space-y-2 pl-1">
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink">ISO 639-1</strong> — Part 1: Alpha-2 code. Two-letter codes for the ~180 major languages most often used in national and bibliographic contexts.
            <span class="block text-xs mt-0.5">
              Registration Authority: <a href={externalLinks.iso639_1RA} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">Library of Congress (ISO 639-1/2 Registration Authority)</a>
              · Standard: <a href={externalLinks.iso639_1Standard} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">ISO 639-1</a>
            </span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink">ISO 639-2</strong> — Part 2: Alpha-3 code. Three-letter codes for ~500 languages; each language may have separate bibliographic (B) and terminological (T) forms.
            <span class="block text-xs mt-0.5">
              Registration Authority: <a href={externalLinks.iso639_2RA} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">Library of Congress</a>
              · Standard: <a href={externalLinks.iso639_2Standard} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">ISO 639-2</a>
            </span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink">ISO 639-3</strong> — Part 3: Alpha-3 code for comprehensive coverage of languages. ~7 900 individual living, extinct, ancient, and historic languages — the most comprehensive of the four parts. The codes ISO 24229 systems reference most often come from this part.
            <span class="block text-xs mt-0.5">
              Registration Authority: <a href={externalLinks.iso639_3RA} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">SIL International</a>
              · Standard: <a href={externalLinks.iso639_3Standard} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">ISO 639-3</a>
            </span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong class="text-ink">ISO 639-5</strong> — Part 5: Alpha-3 code for language families and groups. ~115 collective codes (e.g. <span class="font-mono">afa</span> Afro-Asiatic languages, <span class="font-mono">ira</span> Iranian languages).
            <span class="block text-xs mt-0.5">
              Registration Authority: <a href={externalLinks.iso639_5RA} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">Library of Congress (ISO 639-5 Registration Authority)</a>
              · Standard: <a href={externalLinks.iso639_5Standard} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">ISO 639-5</a>
            </span>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-xs mt-3">
          <a href="/learn/iso639" class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">In-depth guide to ISO 639 →</a>
          · <a href={externalLinks.iso639Standard} class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">ISO 639 family overview on iso.org ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-2 border-blue/50 dark:border-blue-bright/50 pl-5">
        <p class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink mb-1">ISO 15924 — script codes</p>
        <p class="text-sm mb-2">Maintained by the <strong class="text-ink">Unicode Consortium</strong>, appointed by ISO as the Registration Authority. Markus Scherer serves as Registrar. The Unicode Consortium receives and reviews applications for new script codes and changes to existing ones, maintains the authoritative list, processes updates, and publishes a Notice of Changes.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-2">
          <a href="/learn/iso15924" class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">In-depth guide to ISO 15924 →</a>
          · <a href="https://www.unicode.org/iso15924/" class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">ISO 15924 Registration Authority at the Unicode Consortium ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-2 border-gold/60 dark:border-gold-bright/60 pl-5">
        <p class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink mb-1">ISO 24229 — this register</p>
        <p class="text-sm">Maintained by <strong class="text-ink">CalConnect</strong> as the Registration Authority (ISO 24229/RA), designated by ISO. The register is operated by <strong class="text-ink">Ribose</strong>. An Advisory Group (ISO 24229/AG) of 4–12 experts — including a representative of ISO/TC 46 — reviews all submissions.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-2"><a href="/specs/governance" class="text-blue dark:text-blue-bright underline">Full governance and lifecycle →</a></p>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="mt-8 max-w-2xl border-l-2 border-blue/40 dark:border-blue-bright/40 pl-4 py-2">
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
        <strong class="text-ink">Reference data only.</strong> This register indexes ISO 639 and ISO 15924 codes so that systems can reference stable identifiers, but it is <strong>not</strong> the authoritative source for either. For canonical definitions, follow the links above to the relevant registration authority.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Logo + philosophy ──────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section id="logomark" class="rule-section">
    <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row items-start gap-12 mb-10">
      <img
        src="/assets/logos/iso-24229-logo.svg"
        alt="ISO 24229 logomark"
        width="160"
        height="160"
        class="shrink-0 w-28 md:w-40 h-auto"
      />
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow mb-3">The logomark</p>
        <h2 class="max-w-xl">What the shapes are.</h2>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        The ISO 24229 logomark is built from two shapes that share a single origin: <strong class="text-ink">two half-spheres</strong> and <strong class="text-ink">three waves</strong> emanating outward.
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-3">
        <li>
          <strong class="text-ink">The two half-spheres.</strong> They share one origin point — a single meaning, a single thought — but diverge into two halves. The halves stand for the different concepts a meaning can generate across different languages: presence vs absence, definite vs indefinite, this-vs-that definitions that exist in one language but not another. One origin, two conceptions.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong class="text-ink">The three waves.</strong> Three concentric arcs radiate outward from the same origin. They stand for the three forms of expression any meaning can take: writing, reading, and speech. Three forms, all carried from the same source — and, because each can be re-expressed through any of the others, leading to potentially infinite kinds of expression.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        The blank gap between the half-spheres (language) and the waves (script) is where ISO 24229 operates. The standard governs the bridge between language and script — the conversion path that lets a single meaning travel from one written form to another.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Colours ──────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section id="colours" class="rule-section">
    <SectionHead eyebrow="The colours" title="The palette." />
    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        The two half-spheres carry two colour pairs: <strong class="text-ink">blue and red</strong> on one, <strong class="text-ink">cyan and yellow</strong> on the other. These four primaries sit at cardinal points of the colour wheel — no single one dominates, and together they span the full visible spectrum.
      </p>
      <p>
        The three waves that emanate from the half-spheres carry colours blended from the two pairs at their respective angles. The result is a gradient that moves through the spectrum without settling on any one national-signature combination.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
